I’ve transcribed the logic from your handwritten notes into a clean, working Java program. Based on your code, you are demonstrating thread synchronization (or the lack of it) by having two threads share a single Display object to call the wish method.
Here is the implementation with the Main class to start the threads:
class Display {
    // Note: If you add 'synchronized' here, the output will be orderly.
    // Without it, the threads will overlap (race condition).
    public void wish(String name) {
        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            System.out.print("Good Morning: ");
            try {
                Thread.sleep(2000); // 2-second delay as per your notes
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                System.out.println("Thread interrupted");
            }
            System.out.println(name);
        }
    }
}

class MyThread extends Thread {
    Display d;
    String name;

    // Constructor to initialize Display object and the name
    MyThread(Display d, String name) {
        this.d = d;
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void run() {
        d.wish(name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1. Create the shared resource
        Display d = new Display();

        // 2. Create two threads sharing the same Display object
        MyThread t1 = new MyThread(d, "Dhoni");
        MyThread t2 = new MyThread(d, "Yuvraj");

        // 3. Start both threads
        t1.start();
        t2.start();
    }
}

What happens when you run this?
 * The Race Condition: Since the wish method in your notes isn't synchronized, both threads will enter the method at the same time.
 * Mixed Output: Because of the Thread.sleep(2000), you will likely see something like:
   * Good Morning: Good Morning: Dhoni
   * Yuvraj
     This happens because t1 sleeps after printing "Good Morning:", allowing t2 to jump in and print its "Good Morning:" before t1 even finishes its first line.
How to fix it using what we learned?
If you want Dhoni to finish all 10 wishes before Yuvraj starts, you have two choices:
 * The Easy Way: Add the synchronized keyword to the wish method.
 * The Pro Way (ReentrantLock): Use the Lock interface we just discussed!
